In MonoGame.Framework/MathHelper.cs, line 196:

```
        public static object LerpPrecise(float value1, float value2, float amount)
        {
            return ((1 - amount) * value1) + (value2 * amount);
        }
```

Is there a reason this returns an object (which is both useless to API users and involves boxing/GC overhead) rather than a float?

The following code is an example that will trigger the crash:

```
_graphicsManager.PreferredBackBufferWidth = width;
_graphicsManager.PreferredBackBufferHeight = height;
_graphicsManager.IsFullScreen = isFullScreen;
_graphicsManager.ApplyChanges();
```

The ApplyChanges line is what causes it. There is no stack trace at all and no logs that I can find anywhere. Changing anything and calling ApplyChanges is all it takes to repro.

I use MonoGame 3.4 on Windows (Windows DirectX project) with Visual Studio 2015.
I have this texture into DXT1 format:
![t](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5872066/11472683/9848267a-976e-11e5-9f27-6cb796feba33.jpg)

When I use this code:

``` c#
        Texture2D texture;
        SpriteBatch spriteBatch;

        protected override void LoadContent()
        {
            spriteBatch = new SpriteBatch(GraphicsDevice);

            // Load Dxt1 texture (256x256).
            texture = Content.Load<Texture2D>("t");
            byte[] data = new byte[texture.Width * texture.Height / 2]; // Dxt1 correct data size
            texture.GetData(data);
            texture.SetData(data); // Now texture is corrupted.
        }

        protected override void Draw(GameTime gameTime)
        {
            GraphicsDevice.Clear(Color.CornflowerBlue);
            spriteBatch.Begin();

            spriteBatch.Draw(texture, Vector2.Zero, Color.White);

            spriteBatch.End();
            base.Draw(gameTime);
        }
```

I get this result:
![t2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5872066/11473677/00818c72-9774-11e5-951a-804b33fefc64.jpg)

But, the same code with the texture into Color format (ARGB8) work fine.
I have also tried with DXT3 and DXT5 format and it's the same result as DXT1: texture is corrupted.

A previous issue thread https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/issues/3590 suggest to change the type of struct to get texture data to avoid troubles, but no changes for DXT textures this time.

We are currently in the process of porting  the [XUI](https://xui.codeplex.com/), an xbox 360 UI framework, over from XNA to Monogame and we noticed that _GraphicsDevice.Textures[i] = Texture_ is not being set on the GraphicsDevice when a dynamic vertex buffer is applied to it.  **UI_GrayScale.fx**, one of the shaders that have this issue is shown below, we were able to confirm that **UiTransformMatrix**  can be accessed from the vertex shader but the **sampler2D Texture0** is not being passed to the shader.  We merged the fxh header files with the original fx file as we are unsure how to compile both fx and fxh files together with the MGFX tool.

``` hlsl
float4x4    UiTransformMatrix   : register(c0);

// Transform
float4 Transform(float3 position)
{
    float4 p = mul(float4(position, 1.0f), UiTransformMatrix);
    return p;
}

sampler2D   Texture0 : register( s0 );

struct VS_Input
{
    float3 Position : SV_POSITION;
    float4 Color : COLOR0;
    float2 UV0 : TEXCOORD0;
};

struct VS_Output
{
    float4 Position : SV_POSITION;
    float4 Color : COLOR0;
    float2 UV0 : TEXCOORD0;
};

VS_Output VS( VS_Input input )
{
    VS_Output output;

    output.Position = Transform( input.Position.xyz );
    output.Color = input.Color;
    output.UV0 = input.UV0;

    return output;
}

float4 PS( VS_Output input ) : COLOR0
{
    float4 c = input.Color;

    float4 tex0 = tex2D( Texture0, input.UV0 );
    tex0.rgb = dot( tex0.rgb, float3( 0.3f, 0.59f, 0.11f ) );

    c *= tex0;

    return c;
}

technique Technique0
{
    pass Pass0
    {
        VertexShader = compile vs_4_0 VS();
        PixelShader = compile ps_4_0 PS();
    }
}
```

We are applying the parameters for the shader in **SpriteManager.RenderLayer()** as shown below:

``` C#
int textureCount = 0;

if ( pSprite->Texture0.TextureIndex != -1 )
{
    GraphicsDevice.Textures[ textureCount ] = _UI.Texture.Get( pSprite->Texture0.TextureIndex );
    GraphicsDevice.SamplerStates[ textureCount ] = GetSamplerState( pSprite->RenderState.SamplerState0 );
    ++textureCount;
}

Effect effect = _UI.Effect.Get( pSprite->RenderState.Effect );

_UI.Effect.GetParam_UiTransform( pSprite->RenderState.Effect ).SetValue( TransformMatrix ); // can't seem to globally set this - humph
_UI.Effect.SetParams( ref pSprite->RenderState );

effect.CurrentTechnique.Passes[ 0 ].Apply();
```

We have already tried using **effect.Parameters["Texture0"].SetValue(_UI.Texture.Get(pSprite->Texture0.TextureIndex));**  and have also have tried compiling this with _vs_4_0_level_9_1_ and _vs_4_0_level_9_3_ but to no avail.

We draw our data with a dynamic vertex buffer as shown below in the same function:

``` C#
DynamicVB.SetData(VertexPosition * VertexCount * vertexStride, VertexData, 0, pSprite->BatchCount * VertexCount, vertexStride, dataOption);

GraphicsDevice.SetVertexBuffer(DynamicVB);
GraphicsDevice.Indices = DynamicIB;

GraphicsDevice.DrawIndexedPrimitives(PrimitiveType.TriangleList, 0, VertexPosition * VertexCount, pSprite->BatchCount * VertexCount, VertexPosition * IndexCount, pSprite->BatchCount * 2);

VertexPosition += pSprite->BatchCount;

GraphicsDevice.SetVertexBuffer(null);
```

Unfortunately, the best way to reproduce this issue is by downloading [XUI](https://xui.codeplex.com/) and building it.
